goals beyond low-Earth orbit, beyond 2005 when the International Space Station is scheduled to be complete, they are faced with making bigger, brawnier, and incredibly more expensive versions of the chemical rockets in use today.<br><br>Either that, or consider a demonstrated technology that was abandoned almost 30 years ago: nuclear rocket engines...&quot;<br>........from Space.com.<br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>Nuclear rocket engines are the next logical step in reaching out. Promising &quot;airline like access to space&quot; without the antimatter  fusion and warp drives our great grandparents once thought were just around the corner. <br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>Nuclear power is safe and well understood. Any type of engine utilising high energy carries risk, but life is not about eliminating all possible risks. It's about balancing them. When we exchange freedom for security we are selling ourselves short. <br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/spaceh.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>We presently have a very real and practical method of colonising the solar system and it's time to stop listening to the ill informed fearmongers. An exciting new frontier awaits us if we truly want it. <br><br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END-->&quot;the 'N' word&quot;<br><br>Ok, that's enough dramatic impact. The above article is now out of date anyway. Nasa has finally returned to nuclear power. Come have your say and if inclined help us to prevent the ecowackies from holding back progress. <br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>Those pesky anti-technologists have killed off every previous attempt to go nuclear. If you would like to live, work and holiday in space within the not too distant future then add your support to our grassroots movement. <br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/nimoy.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>This isn't science fiction. It's the real deal. Nuclear power has recieved an ill deserved bad rap over the decades. Hollywood gutter science has been selling fear and pop culture crusades were based on ignorance.<br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a676.g.akamai.net/f/676/987/12h/photos.netclubs.com/live/photos/Clubs/t/p/tpeidaeb7nah3e2e0188nkppm4/OrionNow2.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/ujaysin08.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jaysin08</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/7/02 7:47:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=75.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Nuclear Spaceship Engines.</span><hr size=1> It is really unfortunate how nuclear power is treated. We demonstrated the technology in the 60s and would have it today if it wasn't for the fear of a mistake leading in a crash or explosion. We need to take chances to get anywhere. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/uleviethan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Leviethan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/14/02 6:41:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=75.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://leviethan.homestead.com/files/lev_spirit1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Nuclear Spaceship Engines.</span><hr size=1> Yes but there have been enough near accidents (3 mile island, chernobyl) to make the fear understandable especially if the same careful contractors who built those nuclear plants also build a nuclear powered space ship <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wildcat02>wildcat02</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/16/02 5:21:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=75.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Nuclear Spaceship Engines.</span><hr size=1> I suppose it is possible, but there is the possibility of a lot of damage if there is an accident. Think of the Challenger explosion. Now think of the Challenger explosion with a nuclear engine. If NASA messes up, there could be a lot of lives at stake. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/ugr8magus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gr8 Magus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/23/02 10:45:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=75.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.plauder-smilies.d